[3] Gastroenteritis - Kenya (Migori district) officials
Date: Sun 26 Nov 2017
Source: Daily Nation [edited]
http://www.nation.co.ke/news/15-Migori-MCAs-in-hospital-in-Mombasa-after-cholera-scare/1056-4203486-g0i4bt/index.html


15 members of the Migori County Assembly and some county staff were rushed to various private hospitals in Mombasa County on Sun 26 Nov 2017 after a cholera scare. They were suffering from diarrhea and vomiting. Other MCAs [Members of County Assembly] also rushed to hospital for vaccination against cholera due to an outbreak that has so far killed 4 people in Mombasa.

A doctor who treated the ward representatives said they were all treated for food poisoning. "Basically, this means that the food they ate was not cooked well that is why they suffered from food poisoning. We treated quite a number of them who thought it was cholera but we confirmed it is not," said the doctor who requested anonymity.

An affected MCA from Makerero Ward in Kuria West [Migori county], said they ate meat, chicken, fish, rice, and chapati at a hotel on Saturday night, 25 Nov 2017 and afterwards they began feeling unwell. "We were booked at a hotel in Mombasa for 3 days . We were 57 MCAs but only 15 MCAs were affected. I almost died due to diarrhea and vomiting. I was the most affected. The rest were afraid of me; they thought I had cholera," he said. He demanded his medical report to dispatch it to his private doctor in Nairobi. "I have booked a flight to Nairobi. I want to go for further medical examination," he added.

Masaba MCA William Abedi said general observation points to contaminated food. He said he was not sick as he did not eat at the hotel. "We used to do our meetings in this hotel and nobody had ever experienced such. Those who didn't take lunch or dinner at the hotel were not affected, that is how we are saved," said Mr Abedi. "As the assembly we are deeply disturbed by the incident. Family members are calling asking about our health status. This is an unfortunate incident. Samples were taken to laboratory." Mr Abedi said 4 of the MCAs are in critical condition and they will be airlifted for further treatment in Nairobi. "They are fatigued and dehydrated," he added.

[Byline: Winnie Atieno]

